Loving my sautéed cabbage dishes this week!! (ps. Watch yesterdays video!) I typically tend to pick 2-3 cruciferous veggies of the week. This week it’s cabbage and cauliflower. (Next week broccoli and kale). Cruciferous veggies are very underrated, particularly cabbage. If you are estrogen dominant, trying to get pregnant, have a lot of inflammation, weight issues, endocrine dysfunction, to say the least, these should be on your shopping list! However, make sure you speak to your registered dietitian (aka 🙋🏻‍♀️) to make sure that it is right for you as these can interfere with if consumed to closely with thyroid medications. If you do have digestive distress, your dietitian can help you slowlyyyyy add these in, in a way that works best for you, whether in cooked or raw form, as well as portion sizes and pairings. Food, just like medicine, is a science! We all have our own specific individual needs. I am really loving this raw broccoli and herb salad. First of all, It is a great source of all different kinds of vitamins, minerals, antioxidants, phytochemicals, phytonutrients, oemga-3s, fiber, plus so much more. These specific ingredients support healthy hormones and hormone balance, blood sugar stability, weight loss, brain and cardiovascular health, digestion, fertility, and reduces cravings. I chose each ingredient purposefully as they are nutrient dense, but more specifically, support the absorption of certain nutrients. For example: Epidemiological studies provide evidence that a diet rich in broccoli reduces cancer risk and progression. Broccoli is rich in glucosinolates, more available when raw vs cooked. Myrosinase is needed to activate and be able to absorb the antioxidant. Ascorbic acid aka vitamin C is needed to activate myrosinase. To make this salad: simply in a bowl, add 4-6 heads chopped raw broccoli, 2 bunch chopped parsley, 1 bunch chopped cilantro, 1/2 chopped walnuts, 1/2 cranberries, 1/2 sunflower seeds, 2 handfuls chopped red onions, 1/3c EVOO, 1/3c ACV, 1-2 fresh squeezed lemon, dijon mustard, salt pepper and everything bagel seasoning. Mix together, let it sit in the fridge and soak up the flavors. Enjoy!

I am truly in love with this salmon rainbow salad! It is an excellent way to nourish your body, support healthy hormones and hormone balance, blood sugar stability, weight loss, brain and cardiovascular health, digestion, fertility, and reduces cravings. This combo offers all different kinds of vitamins, minerals, antioxidants, phytochemicals, phytonutrients, protein, omega-3s, fiber, plus so much more. These specific ingredients were chosen given their nutrient density and support the absorption of other nutrients. Lucky you, if you are not such a big fan of salmon or fish in general, you have to try this salad as it just might change your mind! I used canned wild salmon as it is much more mild in taste and flavor vs salmon filet. If the fishy smell and taste is what turns you off, then I guarantee you that this salad will help you get those important EPA/DHA omega-3s your brain and body needs in order to function optimally. To make this salad simply in a bowl add canned wild salmon, chopped red and green cabbages, peppers, chickpeas, scallions, artichokes, tomato, parsley, cilantro, hemp seeds, sunflower and pumpkin seeds, feta, apple cider vinegar, fresh squeezed lemon, sea salt, pepper, and everything bagel seasoning. Mix together and Enjoy! This salad easily provides 2 servings.

Cinnamon toast crunch chickpeas! Such a fun and delicious snack, plus super easy to make! Chickpeas are a great source of fiber, manganese, B vitamins including folate, copper, iron, zinc, phosphorus, and magnesium. Chickpeas boosts satiety, decreases cravings, protects against heart disease and diabetes, and boosts nutrient intake. Simply add rinsed chickpeas to a bowl, add 1 tablespoon maple syrup, 1/2 tablespoon cinnamon, 1/4-1/2 tsp nutmeg, and 1 tsp vanilla extract. Mix thoroughly. Bake in the oven at 350F for about 30-35min. Allow to cool and enjoy!

Avocado feta egg salad on the menu for this week! Egg protein has been recognized to be highly digestible and an excellent source of essential amino acids, with the highest attainable protein digestibility per medical studies and journals. Believe it or not, eggs do not affect your cholesterol. This has created so much controversy in the past. Watch my previous video regarding eggs and cholesterol for more details. This dish offers all kinds of important nutrients to support metabolism, immunity, digestion, energy, brain and heart function, weight loss, plus so much more. 
Ingredients:
3 boiled eggs, heaping handful of chopped kale, parsley, radish, cucumber, tomato, red onion, 1/4c chopped Kalamata olives, 1/2 avocado, 1/4c feta, salt and pepper, and fresh squeezed lemon.
Enjoy! xx

Roasted cabbage wedge salad with tomato, feta, garlic topped with sunflower and pumpkin seeds, herbs, and hemp seeds. I mean, mouthwatering so good!! A great side dish to any meal! Cabbage, an incredible versatile cruciferous veggie has a plethora of health benefits. Growing clinical evidence indicates that cabbage has various pharmacological properties against a wide range of diseases such as cardiovascular brain and liver diseases as well as cancer. The chemicals in cabbage have also been shown to optimize hormone health and fertility status, lower inflammation, support digestive health, strengthen the gut microbiome, promote wound healing, reduce excess estrogen. Cabbage has been shown to remarkably protect our mitochondria and reduce reactive oxygen species leading to oxidative stress. Oxidative stress can lead to cell damage and death, mitochondrial dysfunction, therefore causes progression of and development of diseases.
Roast cabbage wedges at 425F topped with your fav seasonings. Do the same with tomato, onions and garlic. Timing is different for all, I roasted for about 30-35min. Top with sunflower seeds, pumpkin seeds, feta, hemp seeds and herbs. Don’t forget to add your protein!
Enjoy! xx

Peanut Butter Coconut Oat Cookies! To make use 1 cup oats, 1/3c shredded unsweetened coconut, 1/4c ground flax, 1c peanut butter powder, 1 tbsp cinnamon, 1 tsp vanilla extract, 1/4c honey, 1c almond milk. Mix everything together, *allow mixture to sit for 5-10min to thicken*, and then place on baking sheet to bake in the oven at 350F for 15-18min. Allow to cool and enjoy! These cookies hit the spot and I was craving exactly this! A cookie high in protein, fiber and omega-3’s with tons of flavor, texture and love! Super easy to make with nutrient dense ingredients that will make you and your body super happy!

Enjoy! xx

Fennel Avocado Lemon Cilantro Salad with sunflower and pumpkin seeds. This salad is full of all kinds of great nutrition! It’s super crunchy and so mouthwatering delicious! 
This salad makes 2-4 servings. 
To made this salad: 
• 1 bulb chopped fennel
• 2c chopped tomato
• 1/4c chopped salted roasted pistachios
• handful chopped cilantro
• 2 tbsp sunflower seeds
• 2 pumpkin seeds
• 1 avocado 
• lemon zest and lemon juice
• black pepper and sea salt to taste
• 2 tbsp extra virgin olive oil 
Mix the ingredients together in a large bowl and get ready to savor each bite! Fennel is well known for its nutrient dense properties and supports a healthy digestive system. Fennel has been shown to contain more than 87 volatile compounds, including the polyphenol antioxidants rosmarinic acid, chlorogenic acid, quercetin, and apigenin. The ingredients in this salad support hormone balance and sexual function, have strong anti-microbial antibacterial and anti-inflammatory properties, protect against disease and cancer, reduce inflammation, reduce cravings, support satiety and weight loss.
Don’t forget to add your protein! 
I hope you enjoy this salad just as much as I do!
Enjoy! xx

Vanilla almond butter protein balls!! These are rich in all kinds of nutrient dense super foods, super easy and fun to make, plus are so dang good! Huge hit in our household! These protein balls are an excellent source of protein, fiber, omega-3s, antioxidants, healthy fats, vitamins and minerals. These are super satiating, support blood sugar stability, reduce inflammation, curb sugar cravings, provide sustainable energy, boost metabolism, support healthy hormones, and will make your tummy super happy! 
To make:
1/2c almond butter
1/4c honey
3/4c oats
1 tbsp vanilla extract 
2/3c vanilla protein powder
2/3c + 2 tbsp ground flax
1 tbsp cinnamon
2 tbsp chia seeds
1/2c almond milk.
Mix ingredients together. Roll into balls and then roll in hemp seeds. Keep in the fridge to cool and enjoy! 
Make sure to share with your loved ones!! xx

Magnesium is an important mineral your body needs in order to function. Magnesium is vital for producing energy, regulating blood sugar and blood pressure, as well as over 300 chemical reactions in the human body. 

•Magnesium has a huge job to make sure your heart, muscles and kidneys all work properly as well as to help build strong teeth and bones. Magnesium supports the maintenance of proper calcium, potassium and zinc levels in the body. Magnesium is one of your important electrolytes that keeps your body going. Think of a battery, full of electrical charge such as cations, anions, protons, electrons, cathodes and anodes. (Don’t quote me on batteries, which is why I am a Dietitian!). The battery can’t function properly without the electrical charges. 

•Make sure to swipe through to learn all about magnesium. These are the basics. There is so much more, but I will spare you on the specificities and very detailed science for another day! For now, be aware of its importance and incorporate these foods into your diet regularly. 

•Make sure to work with a Registered Dietitian to ensure you are properly meeting your nutrition needs for optimal health. •Please note: This post is not to diagnose and treat, it is to educate.

It keeps me on my A++ game and keeps me honest with my nutrition, making sure I am giving my body exactly what it needs. What is PCOS and what can you do to help mitigate symptoms?! PCOS can be managed when working with the right team to support you. Work with your endocrinologist and licensed dietitian 💁🏻‍♀️🙋🏻‍♀️ to help you appropriately and effectively manage your symptoms and reach your goals. Focusing on nutrition, lifestyle and behavioral modifications is key. Eat a diet high in protein and fiber, low carbs, adequate healthy fats, focus on nutrient density, antioxidants and polyphenol rich foods is key! In the video, I said to preface protein, fiber and healthy fats on purpose, which helps to slow down the breakdown and absorption of foods, helping to stabilize blood sugar and increasing satiety. Eating carbs first will quickly be metabolized, causes blood sugar to rise, increases insulin, and will attribute to weight gain and cravings. You do not need to calorie restrict! I will say that a million times over. This puts more stress on the body. It is about nutrition quality, stress management and keeping stress low, regular exercise, sleeping 8-9hrs every night, having a strong support system, and being consistent. Do not forget that consistency is key! The body shifts very quickly with PCOS, as it is an endocrine disorder, closely affecting insulin and blood sugar levels. Specific supplements may or may not be a part of your clinical regimen, which is why working with a medical practitioner, such as your endo and dietitian, can best support you with specific recommendations and prescriptions. Taking recs from google or social media famous individuals may not be your best option and can actually do more harm than good. Make sure the information you receive is from someone who specializes in the field of practice. It will save you time, aggravation, money, and more. Change does not happen over night. Patience is 🔑! #pcos #pcosweightloss #dietitian #pcosdietitian #fertilitydietitian #fertilityjourney #fertility #pcossupport

Why is weight loss such a challenge?! Let’s talk about it quickly in under 90 seconds! I see it all the time! Weight gain and stubborn weight loss due to hormonal imbalances…. well, what can you do? Try taking a look at the entire picture of your life. This includes: stress, sleep, hydration, nutrition quality, alcohol, chemical exposure, physical activity, relationships, and nutritional deficiencies to say the least. It’s like a puzzle. You have to find the right pieces to make it fit and work for you.
Hormonal weight gain can be caused by PCOS, thyroid disorders, androgen imbalances, estrogen dominance, metabolic syndrome, excess cortisol, leptin resistance, pituitary insufficiencies, insulin resistance and more.

Double Chocolate Overnight buckwheat groats! Buckwheat groats are an incredible superfood and is proven in studies to be super beneficial for PCOS, weight loss, gut microbiome health, blood sugar stability, satiety, and reduces inflammation. Buckwheat is actually a gluten free whole grain, a seed, not a nut. It’s great for those with nut allergies, too! It’s an excellent source of B vitamins, magnesium, zinc, fiber, resistant starch fiber, manganese, but also(!!) D-chiro-inositol, Quercetin, Rutin, and Vitexin. These are very beneficial for supporting PCOS and it’s symptoms, reducing inflammation, lowers blood pressure, improves lipid profile, reduces risk for cardiovascular and heart disease, improves blood sugar and weight status.
Super easy and simple Recipe:
1/4c organic buckwheat groats @bobsredmill 
2 tbsp chia seeds
2 tbsp ground flax
Cinnamon, lots!
2 scoops @furtherfood chocolate collagen powder
2 tbsp raw cacao powder
~1-1.5c Coconut almond milk

Hydration by means of drinking water has significant health benefits. Water is the most important nutrient you body needs in order to survive. Believe it or not, we can survive a good amount of time without food, however, this is certainly not the case with water! The body starts to deteriorate rather quickly when dehydration starts to creep and settle in. Wonder why your not losing weight, have significant cravings for salty carbs and sweets, feel sluggish and exhausted, constipated, have hormone disturbances, poor sleep, digestive issues, brain fog, poor skin, and many more symptoms?! Check your hydration status! Drink more water. It does the body good 😉

Let’s talk hormonal balance! To optimize our hormones, which literally run our entire body, think of this as a balance of all factors regarding our overall health. Balancing hormones supports weight loss and healthy weight status, blood sugar balance, digestive heart and brain health, mood, skin, energy, confidence, fertility and menstrual cycles, and so much more. In order to balance our hormones, paying close attention to our nutrition and nutrition quality, sleep, hydration, stress management, physical activity, chemical exposure, are of utmost importance. The details matter! Our body is so good at communicating with us, but many times we ignore, don’t listen, or are so disconnected that the cues are so dim and quiet. The more you pay attention to the details, the more connected you will be, and will be able to pick up what your body needs and is trying to tell you. Work with me and I’ll teach you 😉

Let’s talk HgbA1c and diabetes. What is it, the best range for A1c and the dangers of #diabetes.
Diabetes is a multi-systemic disorder and disease influencing blood glucose regulation. There are different types of Diabetes, type 1 and 2, but now there’s type 3! Diabetes affects our entire body including, heart, brain, kidneys, nerves, liver, eyes, hormones, gut, skin, weight and more. Take care of yourself and your body will take care of you!
